    {
        "content": "<hr>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"306601\">@Kyle Miller</span>  I have followed the Mechanics of Proof course and done every single exercise so far but I do feel I'm missing a proper guide or overview of how to apply lemmas/hypotheses.</p>\n<p>I'm just guessing as I try:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>apply lemma</code></li>\n<li><code>apply lemma at</code></li>\n<li><code>:= lemma</code></li>\n<li><code>:= by apply lemma</code></li>\n<li>more?</li>\n</ul>\n<p>I don't know the difference between the last two for example.</p>",
        "id": 480516358,
        "sender_full_name": "rzeta0",
        "timestamp": 1730750256
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><code>:= lemma</code> means \"<code>lemma</code> is exactly the type i need\". <code>:= by apply lemma</code> means \"you can fill in parameters to <code>lemma</code> (satisfying certain rules) to get a type that is exactly the type i need\"</p>",
        "id": 480517483,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1730750671
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>for example, if the expected type is <code>Nat -&gt; Nat</code>, and <code>foo : (A:Type) -&gt; A -&gt; A</code>, then <code>:= by apply foo</code> works (because lean can figure out that only filling in <code>(A := Nat)</code> gives the right type), but <code>:= foo</code> doesn't.</p>",
        "id": 480517610,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1730750736
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't know what <code>Nat -&gt; Nat</code> means. </p>\n<p>I definitely don't know what <code>foo : (A:Type) -&gt; A -&gt; A</code> means.</p>\n<p>Perhaps an example can illustrate this?</p>",
        "id": 480518466,
        "sender_full_name": "rzeta0",
        "timestamp": 1730751111
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I thought I've seen you write things like <code>apply lemma arg1 arg2</code> before <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"724904\">@rzeta0</span>. Or at least <code>exact lemma arg1 arg2</code>?</p>",
        "id": 480519343,
        "sender_full_name": "Kyle Miller",
        "timestamp": 1730751453
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>aha - i didn't know parameters were written in the signature like that.</p>\n<p>when I see X → Y it looks like functions mapping from domain X to co-domain Y</p>",
        "id": 480520847,
        "sender_full_name": "rzeta0",
        "timestamp": 1730752077
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, <code>Nat -&gt; Nat</code> is the type of mappings from <code>Nat</code> to <code>Nat</code> (natural number sequences).</p>\n<p>And <code>A -&gt; A -&gt; A</code> is the type of mappings from <code>A</code> to <code>A-&gt;A</code>, or in other words (it's often way easier to think of them this way) functions that take two values of type <code>A</code> and return a single value of type <code>A</code>. This is the type of binary operations on <code>A</code>, like addition or multiplication in groups and rings.</p>",
        "id": 480521643,
        "sender_full_name": "Philippe Duchon",
        "timestamp": 1730752380
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>note that <code>(A:Type) -&gt; A -&gt; A</code> is different from <code>A -&gt; A -&gt; A</code>. in the first case, the type of the first parameter is <code>Type</code>, in the second case it is <code>A</code>.</p>",
        "id": 480521767,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1730752440
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>the <code>(A:Type) -&gt; ...</code> notation allows you to <em>give a name</em> to the first parameter, to use it in the returntype.</p>",
        "id": 480521864,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1730752473
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>so <code>(A:Type) -&gt; A -&gt; A</code> is the type of functions which map a type into an endofunction on that type.</p>",
        "id": 480522033,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1730752545
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ah yes you're right, so it's a dependent type where the type of the second parameter depends on the value of the first parameter. Clearly I misread.</p>",
        "id": 480522055,
        "sender_full_name": "Philippe Duchon",
        "timestamp": 1730752553
    }
]